        "fulltext_url": "https://law.emory.edu/elj/_documents/volumes/65/6/vairo.pdf",
        "abstract": "No talk about tort reform can begin without a quote from Shakespeare\u00bfs Henry VI: \u00bfThe first thing we do, let\u00bfs kill all the lawyers.\u00bf There has been a lot of debate about exactly what Shakespeare meant. Was he referring to lawyers as mere parchment pushers who worked to the detriment of the people? Or was he talking about lawyers as a bulwark against tyranny? No matter what Shakespeare meant, I think we can probably agree that right now the modern translation of this quote is \u00bfLet\u00bfs kill all the plaintiffs\u00bf lawyers until we need one.\u00bf This Essay discusses the evolution of tort reform\u00bfbeginning with the seeds of that evolution in the 1960s\u00bfand evaluates whether the reform campaign was successful.",
